## Biography
Initially, Kanasa Mori-sumi joined {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshinaka|en|Minamoto no Yoshinaka|qid=Q1139202|lt=Minamoto no Yoshinaka|1=Minamoto no Yoshinaka}} during the {{ill|Genpei War|en|Genpei War|qid=Q737542|lt=Genpei War|1=Genpei War}} but later returned to his homeland to oversee the {{ill|Misayama Ritual|ja|御射山神事|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Misayama Ritual|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and left his younger brother Mitsumori in his stead. Due to his longstanding affiliation with the {{ill|Heike|ja|平家|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heike|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 伊勢平氏|1=Ise Heishi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q15734686}}, recorded in the ''{{ill|Azuma Kagami|en|Azuma Kagami|qid=Q1042324|lt=Azuma Kagami|1=Azuma Kagami}}'' under the entry for {{ill|Bunji (era)|en|Bunji (era)|qid=Q1194415|lt=Bunji|1=Bunji (era)}} 3 (1187), August 15, Mori-sumi was captured by {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|en|Minamoto no Yoritomo|qid=Q242800|lt=Minamoto no Yoritomo|1=Minamoto no Yoritomo}} and placed under the custody of {{ill|Kajiwara Kagetoki|en|Kajiwara Kagetoki|qid=Q3191855|lt=Kajiwara Kagetoki|1=Kajiwara Kagetoki}}.

Yoritomo initially intended to execute Mori-sumi. However, Kagetoki, recognizing Mori-sumi's skill in {{ill|Kyūjutsu|en|Kyūjutsu|qid=Q11687476|lt=archery|1=Kyūjutsu}}, persuaded Yoritomo to allow Mori-sumi to demonstrate his abilities before his execution. At the {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|en|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|qid=Q701403|lt=Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|1=Tsurugaoka Hachimangū}} during the {{ill|Life release|en|Life release|qid=Q11078912|lt=Hōjōe|1=Life release}}, Mori-sumi performed an exceptional feat of {{ill|Yabusame|en|Yabusame|qid=Q1886157|lt=yabusame|1=Yabusame}}, accurately shooting eight targets, their fragments, and the stands holding them. Impressed, Yoritomo pardoned him. Following Kagetoki's further petitions, several of Yoshinaka's retainers were also spared and became {{ill|Gokenin|en|Gokenin|qid=Q63765|lt=gokenin|1=Gokenin}}.<ref>[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E8%AB%8F%E8%A8%AA%E7%9B%9B%E6%BE%84-1084644 ''Suwa Mori-sumi''] - Kotobank</ref>

In {{ill|Kenkyū|en|Kenkyū|qid=Q1193933|lt=Kenkyū|1=Kenkyū}} 4 (1193), Mori-sumi accompanied Yoritomo on hunts in {{ill|Shimotsuke Province|en|Shimotsuke Province|qid=Q1053699|lt=Shimotsuke Province|1=Shimotsuke Province}} and {{ill|Kōzuke Province|en|Kōzuke Province|qid=Q1054838|lt=Kōzuke Province|1=Kōzuke Province}}, where he continued to serve at ceremonial events involving archery. By 1203, his activities are still noted in historical records. In modern-day {{ill|Shimosuwa|en|Shimosuwa|qid=Q1204211|lt=Shimosuwa|1=Shimosuwa}}, a mound called "Kajiwara Zuka" commemorates Mori-sumi's gratitude to Kagetoki.

